<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="355" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,1122,1593]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,224,1122,1145]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="PIC M." box="[230,355,1122,1145]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref20247" refString="PIC M. 1926 b: Nouveautes diverses. Melanges Exotico-Entomologiques 47: 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1926">PIC (1926b)</bibRefCitation>
described this species presumably based on a single specimen as the description is written in singular and only a single length measurement was given. Therefore I consider the specimen 
<typeStatus box="[377,470,1186,1209]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">holotype</typeStatus>
by monotypy. Pic placed the species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Harold, 1875" authorityName="Harold" authorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Amplipalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Amplipalpa</emphasis>
Harold, 1875
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1859" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1859" box="[357,606,1218,1241]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oediopalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[357,483,1218,1241]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Oediopalpa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BALY J. S." box="[490,606,1218,1241]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" refId="ref19430" refString="BALY J. S. 1859: Catalogue of Hispidae in the collection of the British Museum. Part I. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 172 pp. + 9 pls." type="book" year="1859">Baly, 1859</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) and compared it to 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1923" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1923" box="[824,1086,1218,1241]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Amplipalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveipennis">
<emphasis box="[824,975,1218,1241]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">A. foveipennis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="PIC M." box="[981,1086,1218,1241]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref20214" refString="PIC M. 1923: Nouveautes diverses. Melanges Exotico-Entomologiques 38: 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1923">Pic, 1923</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1926" box="[113,322,1250,1273]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Amplipalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atripes">
<emphasis box="[113,322,1250,1273]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Amplipalpa atripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
since its description has been listed only in catalogues (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="UHMANN E." pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="1 - 153" refId="ref20731" refString="UHMANN E. 1957 a: Chrysomelidae: Hispinae. Hispinae Americanae. In: HINCKS W. D. (ed.): Coleopterorum Catalogus Supplementa, Pars 35, Fasc. 1. Dr. W. Junk, 's-Gravenhage, vii + pp. 1 - 153." type="book chapter" year="1957">UHMANN 1957a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="UHMANN E." box="[192,250,1282,1305]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="399 - 490" refId="ref20824" refString="UHMANN E. 1964: Chrysomelidae: Hispinae. Corrigenda et Addenda. In: STEEL W. O. (ed.): Coleopterorum Catalogus Supplementa. Pars 35. Fasc. 3. W. Junk, 's-Gravenhage, v + pp. 399 - 490." type="book chapter" year="1964">1964</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,1122,1593]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1127,220,307]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="355" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">
I have studied the 
<typeStatus box="[345,438,1314,1337]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">holotype</typeStatus>
and the species does not belong to the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chapuis" authorityYear="1875" box="[925,1058,1314,1337]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" rank="tribe" tribe="Spilophorini">Spilophorini</taxonomicName>
as it has setigerous pores present only in anterior corners of pronotum. I find that it belongs to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevrolat in Dejean" authorityYear="1836" box="[113,243,1378,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[113,243,1378,1401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Cephaloleia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it fits with the concept of that genus (
<bibRefCitation author="SEKERKA L." box="[678,833,1378,1401]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="257 - 314" refId="ref20282" refString="SEKERKA L. 2014: Review of Imatidiini genera (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Cassidinae). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae 54: 257 - 314." type="journal article" year="2014">SEKERKA 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevrolat in Dejean" authorityYear="1836" box="[937,1067,1378,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[937,1067,1378,1401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Cephaloleia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is very distinct and easy to separate because it has metallic blue elytra, serrate latero-apical margins of elytra, head abruptly constricted behind eyes and vertex separated from head by a deep sulcus thus the eyes appear to project laterally. There are only five uniformly metallic blue species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevrolat in Dejean" authorityYear="1836" box="[278,408,1506,1529]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[278,408,1506,1529]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Cephaloleia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1875" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1875" box="[423,692,1506,1529]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caeruleata">
<emphasis box="[423,568,1506,1529]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">C. caeruleata</emphasis>
Baly, 1875
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Uhmann, 1948" authorityName="Uhmann" authorityYear="1948" box="[703,984,1506,1529]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dilatata">
<emphasis box="[703,817,1506,1529]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">C. dilatata</emphasis>
Uhmann, 1948
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1875" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emarginata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">C. emarginata</emphasis>
Baly, 1875
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1885" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1885" box="[312,596,1538,1561]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallescens">
<emphasis box="[312,477,1538,1561]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">C. metallescens</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BALY J. S." box="[483,596,1538,1561]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" pagination="1 - 72" refId="ref19503" refString="BALY J. S. 1885: Hispidae. Pp. 1 - 72. In: GODMAN F. D. &amp; SALVIN O. (eds): Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Coleoptera. Vol. VI. Part 2. Phytophaga (part). Taylor &amp; Francis, London, x + 249 pp. + 13 pls." type="book chapter" year="1885">Baly, 1885</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Baly, 1859" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1859" box="[645,871,1538,1561]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarsata">
<emphasis box="[645,751,1538,1561]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">C. tarsata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BALY J. S." box="[755,871,1538,1561]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" refId="ref19430" refString="BALY J. S. 1859: Catalogue of Hispidae in the collection of the British Museum. Part I. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 172 pp. + 9 pls." type="book" year="1859">Baly, 1859</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) all differing in head continuously constricted behind eyes without sulcus separating vertex. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sekerka" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Pic" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[877,1088,1570,1593]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atripes">
<emphasis box="[877,1088,1570,1593]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Cephaloleia atripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also quite unusual shape of pronotum as it has anterior corners obliquely truncate (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="14.[151,190,1422,1441]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,225,1367]" captionTargetId="figure-10@14.[151,1126,225,1367]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs. 1–8. 1 – Cephaloleia apertura (Staines, 2013) (holotype, 4.3 mm); 2 – Cephaloleia atripes (Pic, 1926) (holotype, 5.1 mm); 3 – Cephaloleia fernandoi (Bondar, 1940) (paratype, LSPC, 6.3 mm); 4 – Cephaloleia opaca Baly, 1859 (Rio de Janeiro: Trinidad, LSPC, 6.0 mm); 5 – Cephaloleia impressa Uhmann, 1930 (holotype, 3.5 mm); 6 – Demothispa clermonti Pic, 1934 (holotype, 3.5 mm); 7 – Cephaloleia jataiensis (Pic, 1923) (holotype, 4.2 mm); 14 – Xenispa aeneipennis (Baly, 1859) (holotype, 3.7 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5316266" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5316266/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="355">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) while all uniformly metallic blue species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevrolat in Dejean" authorityYear="1836" box="[650,780,252,275]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[650,780,252,275]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="355">Cephaloleia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have anterior corners rounded. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,298,284,307]" pageId="4" pageNumber="355">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[304,373,284,307]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="355">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion box="[383,445,284,307]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="4" pageNumber="355">Goiás</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="DESCARPENTRIES A. &amp; VILLIERS A." box="[460,813,284,307]" pageId="4" pageNumber="355" pagination="137 - 154" refId="ref19929" refString="DESCARPENTRIES A. &amp; VILLIERS A. 1959: Les types de la collection M. Pic. I. Chrysomelinae et Hispinae du nouveau-monde. Bulletin du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle Paris 31: 137 - 154." type="journal article" year="1959">DESCARPENTRIES &amp; VILLIERS 1959</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
